WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.705 --> 00:00:05.607
<i>- Hey. you're not nervous</i>
<i>I'm gonna embarrass you</i>

2
00:00:05.640 --> 00:00:06.808
in front of your old captain.
are you?

3
00:00:06.841 --> 00:00:07.575
- Of course not.

4
00:00:07.609 --> 00:00:08.576
I don't know why
I'm so anxious.

5
00:00:08.610 --> 00:00:11.411
Russ has always been one
of my biggest champions.

6
00:00:11.445 --> 00:00:13.815
He's the one that pushed me to
go to officer candidate school

7
00:00:13.848 --> 00:00:14.849
after my first tour.

8
00:00:14.883 --> 00:00:16.584
- Well. I'm sure he's not
coming all the way to LA

9
00:00:16.618 --> 00:00:18.385
so that he can tell you
he's disappointed in you.

10
00:00:18.418 --> 00:00:19.721
- I just wish he would give me

11
00:00:19.754 --> 00:00:21.421
some sort of idea
what this is about.

12
00:00:21.455 --> 00:00:22.724
but that's Russ.

13
00:00:22.757 --> 00:00:24.526
- There she is.
- Hey. Russ!

14
00:00:24.559 --> 00:00:26.493
It's so good to see you!
- Ah!

15
00:00:26.528 --> 00:00:28.428
- Hey.
- John Nolan.

16
00:00:28.462 --> 00:00:31.365
- Colonel Russell Wilkes.
Please. call me Russ.

17
00:00:31.398 --> 00:00:33.768
It's a pleasure to finally meet
the man behind the stories.

18
00:00:33.801 --> 00:00:36.638
- Yeah. likewise. Sit down.
- Thank you.

19
00:00:36.671 --> 00:00:38.840
I really appreciate
you being here. John.

20
00:00:38.873 --> 00:00:40.842
I know I didn't give away
too much over the phone.

21
00:00:40.875 --> 00:00:43.343
but what I'm here to discuss
would affect both your lives.

22
00:00:43.377 --> 00:00:46.313
Seems only fair to include you
in the conversation.

23
00:00:46.346 --> 00:00:48.248
The Sec Def has tasked me
with putting together

24
00:00:48.282 --> 00:00:49.684
a working group
inside the Pentagon.

25
00:00:49.717 --> 00:00:51.318
- Wow.

26
00:00:51.351 --> 00:00:52.820
- A team of my own choosing
that will spearhead

27
00:00:52.854 --> 00:00:55.590
bringing battlefield medicine
into the 22nd century.

28
00:00:55.623 --> 00:00:58.458
It's the most consequential
assignment of my career.

29
00:00:58.492 --> 00:01:01.328
and you are the first person
I'm asking to be a part of it.

30
00:01:04.666 --> 00:01:06.199
<i>- I mean. it's an honor</i>
<i>just to be nominated.</i>

31
00:01:06.233 --> 00:01:08.335
- Totally. Russ is a genius.

32
00:01:08.368 --> 00:01:10.605
He could recruit anyone
for this working group.

33
00:01:10.638 --> 00:01:12.607
And the fact that
he called me first--

34
00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:14.609
I mean. that's--
that's pretty great.

35
00:01:14.642 --> 00:01:16.678
- Yeah. 100%. That's so cool.

36
00:01:16.711 --> 00:01:19.346
But. I mean. our life
is perfect right now.

37
00:01:19.379 --> 00:01:21.248
There's no way
we're messing that up.

38
00:01:21.281 --> 00:01:23.417
- No way. It's perfect.

39
00:01:29.289 --> 00:01:30.558
- Police! Get down!

40
00:01:30.592 --> 00:01:32.326
- This is Bailey Nune. LAFD.

41
00:01:32.359 --> 00:01:34.428
I need an RA
to Central Station Market.

42
00:01:34.461 --> 00:01:36.363
We have a male GSW victim

43
00:01:36.396 --> 00:01:38.231
who's been shot in the head
and the back.

44
00:01:38.265 --> 00:01:40.868
- Two suspects--black hoodies.
masks. and pants.

45
00:01:40.902 --> 00:01:43.136
One headed east
towards Broadway.

46
00:01:43.170 --> 00:01:44.471
In pursuit of second suspect.

47
00:01:44.505 --> 00:01:45.773
Move! Move!

48
00:02:14.502 --> 00:02:16.370
Why are you texting me
when I'm right here?

49
00:02:16.403 --> 00:02:18.238
- Letting you sleep.
- That's sweet.

50
00:02:18.271 --> 00:02:20.307
Wait. are you looking
at real estate?

51
00:02:20.340 --> 00:02:22.209
- We have to upgrade.

52
00:02:22.242 --> 00:02:23.811
We need more room--

53
00:02:23.845 --> 00:02:27.515
a second tub. a closet
that fits all our clothes.

54
00:02:27.548 --> 00:02:30.183
- I mean. yeah. sure.
that would be nice. but...

55
00:02:30.217 --> 00:02:31.719
we created our family here.

56
00:02:31.753 --> 00:02:34.321
- Which I love. but now
we're bursting at the seams.

57
00:02:34.354 --> 00:02:37.558
and Mama's ready to crack open
that trust fund and get crazy.

58
00:02:37.592 --> 00:02:39.359
- Mm. I'm not sure
I like the sound of that.

59
00:02:39.393 --> 00:02:40.494
- Tough.

60
00:02:40.528 --> 00:02:42.530
We have money.
- Uh. no.

61
00:02:42.563 --> 00:02:44.398
We have some money.

62
00:02:44.431 --> 00:02:46.601
But housing prices in LA
are insane.

63
00:02:48.803 --> 00:02:50.705
I guess it couldn't hurt
to see what's out there.

64
00:02:50.738 --> 00:02:52.507
- I love that you've learned
to roll with me.

65
00:02:52.540 --> 00:02:53.908
rather than resisting.

66
00:02:53.941 --> 00:02:56.343
- Yes. you have successfully
broken my spirit.

67
00:02:56.376 --> 00:02:57.578
- Yay.
- Yay.

68
00:02:59.413 --> 00:03:01.683
Quickie
before the kids wake up?

69
00:03:01.716 --> 00:03:04.317
- Oh. um. well...

70
00:03:04.351 --> 00:03:06.319
Mm.

71
00:03:06.353 --> 00:03:07.689
- Mom. come here!

72
00:03:09.791 --> 00:03:11.726
Too late.

73
00:03:11.759 --> 00:03:13.260
<i>- I like this one.</i>

74
00:03:13.293 --> 00:03:14.896
I bet you could hang
a swing set

75
00:03:14.929 --> 00:03:16.798
from that tree
right there in the back.

76
00:03:16.831 --> 00:03:19.466
- That was my favorite
until I saw this.

77
00:03:19.499 --> 00:03:24.438
It has a pool and a gym
and a screening room.

78
00:03:24.471 --> 00:03:26.541
- Wait. hold up. You got
screening room kind of money?

79
00:03:26.574 --> 00:03:28.275
- Depends on which one
of us you ask.

80
00:03:28.308 --> 00:03:30.410
Wesley is the king
of frugality.

81
00:03:30.444 --> 00:03:31.946
so he would definitely say no.

82
00:03:31.979 --> 00:03:34.347
but I lived on credit cards
until I met him.

83
00:03:34.381 --> 00:03:36.684
so I'm way more comfortable
pushing the envelope.

84
00:03:36.718 --> 00:03:39.352
- Hey. Nolan.
did you tell Officer Hart

85
00:03:39.386 --> 00:03:42.623
that the shooters last night
were furries?

86
00:03:42.657 --> 00:03:45.459
- No. I said they were
wearing hoodies.

87
00:03:45.492 --> 00:03:46.894
Are you taking the case?
- Yeah.

88
00:03:46.928 --> 00:03:48.529
Do you mind just walking us
through it?

89
00:03:48.563 --> 00:03:50.565
- Yeah. uh. Bailey and I were
coming back from dinner

90
00:03:50.598 --> 00:03:51.799
at Central Station Market.

91
00:03:51.833 --> 00:03:53.433
- Date night?
- No.

92
00:03:53.467 --> 00:03:55.903
Her former commanding officer
came to offer her a job--

93
00:03:55.937 --> 00:03:57.772
a Pentagon think tank.

94
00:03:57.805 --> 00:03:59.874
- Wow. you really married
outside of your league.

95
00:03:59.907 --> 00:04:01.308
- I know. right?

96
00:04:01.341 --> 00:04:02.777
- So is she going to take it?
- No.

97
00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:04.444
It would mean relocating
to D.C..

98
00:04:04.478 --> 00:04:05.713
so it's a nonstarter for us.

99
00:04:05.747 --> 00:04:07.515
- I mean. it might be
a nonstarter for you.

100
00:04:07.548 --> 00:04:09.517
but I guarantee you that
your overachiever of a wife

101
00:04:09.550 --> 00:04:11.919
is seriously thinking about it.
- No. actually.

102
00:04:11.953 --> 00:04:14.555
She was laughing it off
when we talked about--

103
00:04:14.589 --> 00:04:17.525
oh. my God. she's actually
thinking about it seriously.

104
00:04:17.558 --> 00:04:19.527
Okay. well. no. no.
if that's something

105
00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:21.562
she really wants to do.
relocating to D.C.

106
00:04:21.596 --> 00:04:23.064
could be cool.
- It's not.

107
00:04:23.097 --> 00:04:25.365
I spent time there
during my joint-ops days.

108
00:04:25.398 --> 00:04:27.602
It took me about three weeks
to unclench

109
00:04:27.635 --> 00:04:29.402
every time I came home.

110
00:04:29.436 --> 00:04:30.972
- Thank you for that insight.
- Mm.

111
00:04:31.005 --> 00:04:32.540
- So any clarity
on the victim?

112
00:04:32.573 --> 00:04:34.976
- Fred Wilson. 48. CPA.

113
00:04:35.009 --> 00:04:37.444
married. no kids.
no criminal record.

114
00:04:37.477 --> 00:04:39.312
- Making him
an unlikely candidate

115
00:04:39.346 --> 00:04:41.015
for a targeted assassination.

116
00:04:41.048 --> 00:04:42.617
- Is there anything else
about the shooters

117
00:04:42.650 --> 00:04:44.552
that you didn't give Hart?

118
00:04:44.585 --> 00:04:46.654
- Sorry. I did not get
a good look at them.

119
00:04:46.687 --> 00:04:48.455
What about CCTV?
Anything there?

120
00:04:48.488 --> 00:04:50.457
- They were pretty covered up.

121
00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:53.393
But take a look at this.

122
00:04:58.666 --> 00:05:00.501
- Uh. looks like
the letters SF.

123
00:05:00.535 --> 00:05:01.836
That would make him
Southern Front.

124
00:05:01.869 --> 00:05:05.540
No visible tattoos
on the second shooter.

125
00:05:05.573 --> 00:05:07.074
Huh.
- Yeah.

126
00:05:07.108 --> 00:05:09.977
- So why would a member
of a white supremacist gang

127
00:05:10.011 --> 00:05:11.712
partner up with a Black man

128
00:05:11.746 --> 00:05:13.915
to execute a civilian
in broad daylight?

129
00:05:13.948 --> 00:05:16.349
- Told you he'd spot it.
- You trained him well.

130
00:05:16.383 --> 00:05:18.418
- Could be
that our innocent CPA

131
00:05:18.451 --> 00:05:20.755
was helping the Southern Front
to launder money.

132
00:05:20.788 --> 00:05:23.791
or maybe he had a drug problem
and owed them money.

133
00:05:23.825 --> 00:05:26.093
- We're trying to get the ME
to rush the tox screen.

134
00:05:26.127 --> 00:05:28.395
but he's dodging our calls.
- Oh. say no more.

135
00:05:28.428 --> 00:05:29.730
I'll go deliver the ask
in person.

136
00:05:29.764 --> 00:05:31.364
Let me collect my boot.

137
00:05:33.601 --> 00:05:34.735
- Hey.

138
00:05:34.769 --> 00:05:37.404
Do you know what this is?
- An iron?

139
00:05:37.437 --> 00:05:39.439
- You know what it's not?
A machete.

140
00:05:39.472 --> 00:05:41.576
I am due in court
in two hours to testify

141
00:05:41.609 --> 00:05:44.045
about a man attacking people
on a bus with a machete.

142
00:05:44.078 --> 00:05:45.713
- Okay. something must
have got switched around

143
00:05:45.746 --> 00:05:47.114
in the evidence locker--
we'll figure it out.

144
00:05:47.148 --> 00:05:49.416
- No. no. no.
The case is time not waived.

145
00:05:49.449 --> 00:05:52.153
If we don't find it fast. that
psycho is going to be let free.

146
00:05:52.186 --> 00:05:53.588
- Okay. have you told
the prosecutor?

147
00:05:53.621 --> 00:05:55.623
- No. It's Wesley.

148
00:05:55.656 --> 00:05:57.158
And I am just trying to keep
him in blissful ignorance

149
00:05:57.191 --> 00:05:58.960
as long as possible.

150
00:05:58.993 --> 00:06:00.027
Help me.

151
00:06:00.061 --> 00:06:01.829
- That's the case number.

152
00:06:01.863 --> 00:06:04.065
- No. I know. but it's wrong.
- The case number isn't wrong.

153
00:06:04.098 --> 00:06:08.135
The item might be wrong.
but numbers are just numbers.

154
00:06:08.169 --> 00:06:09.704
- Fine.

155
00:06:09.737 --> 00:06:13.473
Um. so the--the point is.
I have to be at court.

156
00:06:13.507 --> 00:06:15.109
uh. and--and I need
that machete. like. ASAP.

157
00:06:15.142 --> 00:06:17.178
- Case number?
- Oh.

158
00:06:17.211 --> 00:06:19.180
- We're not gonna find it
by using the case number.

159
00:06:19.213 --> 00:06:20.848
The numbers got switched.

160
00:06:20.882 --> 00:06:22.449
- Well. if you don't have
the case number.

161
00:06:22.482 --> 00:06:23.784
then I can't help you.
- Oh. Wesley's gonna kill me.

162
00:06:23.818 --> 00:06:27.487
- It's--relax.
Maybe it's just a typo. right?

163
00:06:27.521 --> 00:06:29.023
The first eight numbers
are the date.

164
00:06:29.056 --> 00:06:33.460
The crime was on January 20th?
Try 20-10-2026.

165
00:06:36.964 --> 00:06:39.133
Try 02-01-2026.

166
00:06:41.468 --> 00:06:43.436
- Wow.
- 20-01-2025.

167
00:06:49.777 --> 00:06:51.712
- Are you sure you used
the new data-entry procedure?

168
00:06:51.746 --> 00:06:53.748
We changed it a few months ago.
- Of course I did.

169
00:06:55.950 --> 00:06:58.152
But I wasn't the one
who logged the entry

170
00:06:58.185 --> 00:06:59.954
because you wouldn't approve
the overtime.

171
00:06:59.987 --> 00:07:01.122
I had Smitty do it.

172
00:07:03.758 --> 00:07:05.226
- What the hell
is your problem?

173
00:07:05.259 --> 00:07:06.961
- Uh. good morning?

174
00:07:06.994 --> 00:07:09.563
- I have bent over
backwards to treat you well.

175
00:07:09.597 --> 00:07:11.032
and this is how you repay me.
- I don't--

176
00:07:11.065 --> 00:07:12.800
I'm sorry. I don't know
what's happening right now.

177
00:07:12.833 --> 00:07:14.068
- Like hell.

178
00:07:14.101 --> 00:07:15.870
You know.
your little innocent act

179
00:07:15.903 --> 00:07:18.673
would be a lot more believable
if they weren't in your office.

180
00:07:18.706 --> 00:07:20.107
Just know this:
if you go through with it.

181
00:07:20.141 --> 00:07:21.776
I will do everything
in my power

182
00:07:21.809 --> 00:07:24.145
to absolutely destroy you.

183
00:07:30.017 --> 00:07:31.218
- Hi. Who are you?

184
00:07:31.252 --> 00:07:32.720
What are you doing
in my office.

185
00:07:32.753 --> 00:07:34.689
and why has it sent Vivian
into a rage spiral?

186
00:07:34.722 --> 00:07:37.158
- Rita Sanchez.
This is Bradley Worth.

187
00:07:37.191 --> 00:07:39.093
We work
with the Democratic Party.

188
00:07:39.126 --> 00:07:41.494
and we want you
to run for district attorney.

189
00:07:41.529 --> 00:07:43.597
- And now it makes sense.

190
00:07:43.631 --> 00:07:45.232
That's a hard no for me.
by the way.

191
00:07:45.266 --> 00:07:46.867
but thanks for stopping by.
- You obviously know

192
00:07:46.901 --> 00:07:48.536
that Vivian Eckert's
running unopposed

193
00:07:48.569 --> 00:07:50.004
since Del Monte dropped
out of the race.

194
00:07:50.037 --> 00:07:51.939
- Yeah. but that was a month
ago--why come to me now?

195
00:07:51.973 --> 00:07:54.041
- Candidly. we've been having
a hard time finding someone

196
00:07:54.075 --> 00:07:56.243
to take up his mantle.

197
00:07:56.277 --> 00:07:59.046
So I'm your last choice.
- Hardly.

198
00:08:01.582 --> 00:08:04.151
Look. Mr. Evers.
I wish there was time

199
00:08:04.185 --> 00:08:07.755
for us to do our usual dance
of seduction and ego stroking.

200
00:08:07.788 --> 00:08:09.890
But as you rightly pointed
out. we're up against it.

201
00:08:09.924 --> 00:08:12.026
The deadline to enter this race
is in three days.

202
00:08:12.059 --> 00:08:13.694
- And Vivian becoming DA
is worst-case scenario

203
00:08:13.728 --> 00:08:15.062
for the people of this city.

204
00:08:15.096 --> 00:08:16.864
I mean. she has
the most regressive record

205
00:08:16.897 --> 00:08:18.532
in your office.
- Oh. I agree.

206
00:08:18.566 --> 00:08:19.834
But there's zero chance
of me beating her.

207
00:08:19.867 --> 00:08:21.535
I was temporarily disbarred.

208
00:08:21.569 --> 00:08:23.704
- Because of your dealings
with Elijah Stone--we know.

209
00:08:23.738 --> 00:08:25.806
- Yeah. and we are prepared
to embrace that.

210
00:08:25.840 --> 00:08:28.642
I mean. you're a hero who put
his life and career on the line

211
00:08:28.676 --> 00:08:30.845
to take down
a very dangerous kingpin.

212
00:08:30.878 --> 00:08:32.913
Voters love a man who's willing
to stand up for what's right.

213
00:08:32.947 --> 00:08:35.316
- Not to mention you're married
to a cop.

214
00:08:35.349 --> 00:08:37.885
which automatically makes you
a more attractive candidate

215
00:08:37.918 --> 00:08:39.620
to anyone worried
that progressive

216
00:08:39.653 --> 00:08:41.188
means soft on crime.

217
00:08:41.222 --> 00:08:43.891
- Look. I don't want Vivian
to win any more than you do.

218
00:08:43.924 --> 00:08:45.726
but I--
- But nothing.

219
00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:47.962
A Vivian victory will hurt
a lot of people.

220
00:08:47.995 --> 00:08:50.297
And right now you're
our last hope at stopping her.

221
00:08:50.331 --> 00:08:53.200
It may be a long shot.
but isn't it worth the risk?

222
00:08:56.003 --> 00:08:57.738
- I thought you didn't have
time to stroke my ego.

223
00:08:59.940 --> 00:09:02.810
- You have to let me see him.
- I-I don't. actually.

224
00:09:02.843 --> 00:09:05.179
- On TV. the family has
to identify the body.

225
00:09:05.212 --> 00:09:07.081
- Yeah. we don't do that
anymore.

226
00:09:07.114 --> 00:09:08.616
- Ugh. please--
- That's right. ma'am.

227
00:09:08.649 --> 00:09:09.884
It's no longer policy.

228
00:09:09.917 --> 00:09:11.852
But trust me.
it's for the best.

229
00:09:11.886 --> 00:09:14.055
Seeing your loved
one like that. it--

230
00:09:14.088 --> 00:09:16.924
it changes how you
remember them forever.

231
00:09:16.957 --> 00:09:20.161
- I don't understand.
Fred was a saint.

232
00:09:20.194 --> 00:09:22.229
Why would someone
want to kill him?

233
00:09:22.263 --> 00:09:25.066
- Well. that's what
we're trying to figure out.

234
00:09:25.099 --> 00:09:27.101
- He's really dead?

235
00:09:27.134 --> 00:09:28.936
- Yes. ma'am. I'm afraid so.

236
00:09:28.969 --> 00:09:30.704
And we are so sorry
for your loss.

237
00:09:30.738 --> 00:09:33.040
Okay.

238
00:09:33.074 --> 00:09:35.209
Thank you.

239
00:09:37.344 --> 00:09:39.613
- Thanks for the assist.

240
00:09:39.647 --> 00:09:41.682
Grief makes people
a little crazy.

241
00:09:41.715 --> 00:09:43.818
and I don't like dealing
with them when they're normal.

242
00:09:43.851 --> 00:09:45.352
- Why you work with the dead.
I suppose.

243
00:09:47.822 --> 00:09:50.224
- Uh. anything jump out at you
at the preliminary autopsy?

244
00:09:50.257 --> 00:09:52.660
- No. uh. run-of-the-mill
gun homicide.

245
00:09:52.693 --> 00:09:54.395
The bullet to the head
killed him instantly.

246
00:09:54.428 --> 00:09:56.831
but the shot to the body
was fatal as well.

247
00:09:56.864 --> 00:09:58.132
- Any signs of drug use?

248
00:09:58.165 --> 00:10:00.768
- No. but the tox screen
is underway.

249
00:10:00.801 --> 00:10:03.704
I'll let Harper and Lopez know
the second it comes in.

250
00:10:03.737 --> 00:10:05.639
- Perfect. Thank you very much.
- Yep.

251
00:10:05.673 --> 00:10:07.141
<i>- I once had a widower insist</i>

252
00:10:07.174 --> 00:10:09.677
on seeing his wife's body
back when I was in Sugar Land.

253
00:10:09.710 --> 00:10:11.812
Ended up suing the city
for mental anguish.

254
00:10:11.846 --> 00:10:13.380
- Did he win?
- No.

255
00:10:13.414 --> 00:10:16.150
Case got dismissed when he
was convicted of her murder.

256
00:10:16.183 --> 00:10:19.220
- Oh.

257
00:10:19.253 --> 00:10:21.222
Hey! Police! Let her go!
- Whoa! Hey!

258
00:10:21.255 --> 00:10:22.990
Hi. hi.
It's all--it's all good.

259
00:10:23.023 --> 00:10:24.825
She's--she's fine.
- I'm fine.

260
00:10:24.859 --> 00:10:26.727
- Yeah. I can see that.

261
00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:28.796
But two minutes ago.
you were grieving.

262
00:10:28.829 --> 00:10:30.097
- I'm still grieving.

263
00:10:30.131 --> 00:10:32.333
It manifests itself
in unknowable ways.

264
00:10:32.366 --> 00:10:34.168
- Right. but you brought
your boyfriend

265
00:10:34.201 --> 00:10:36.003
to help you identify
your husband's body?

266
00:10:36.036 --> 00:10:39.306
- Well. I needed
emotional support?

267
00:10:39.340 --> 00:10:42.042
- She's very sensitive.
- Yeah.

268
00:10:42.076 --> 00:10:43.777
Well. you can emotionally
support each other

269
00:10:43.811 --> 00:10:45.679
on the way
to the station--let's go.

270
00:10:45.713 --> 00:10:46.981
- Oh.
- This way.

271
00:10:47.014 --> 00:10:48.015
- This way?
- Yes.

272
00:10:48.048 --> 00:10:49.316
- Oh. no.
- Put your hands down.

273
00:10:49.350 --> 00:10:50.918
- Yes. sir.
- Wow.

274
00:10:52.920 --> 00:10:55.823
- I know this looks bad.
- Understatement.

275
00:10:55.856 --> 00:10:58.259
Your husband was murdered.
and in less than 24 hours.

276
00:10:58.292 --> 00:11:00.427
you were getting busy
with your side piece

277
00:11:00.461 --> 00:11:02.396
down the hall from his body.

278
00:11:02.429 --> 00:11:04.365
- I didn't even want
to be there.

279
00:11:04.398 --> 00:11:06.934
Uh. I told Faith
it would look weird.

280
00:11:06.967 --> 00:11:09.236
but she insisted.

281
00:11:09.270 --> 00:11:11.872
- So you were just trying to be
a good boyfriend.

282
00:11:11.906 --> 00:11:14.708
- Todd is a terrible boyfriend.

283
00:11:14.742 --> 00:11:18.078
He's a lot of fun. but anything
that requires emotional depth--

284
00:11:18.112 --> 00:11:19.980
- Okay. what about Fred?
What was he like?

285
00:11:20.014 --> 00:11:23.784
- He was always super cool
anytime that I came by.

286
00:11:23.817 --> 00:11:26.253
- You're saying Fred knew
about the affair?

287
00:11:26.287 --> 00:11:29.423
- It wasn't an affair.
It was an open marriage.

288
00:11:29.456 --> 00:11:31.859
The whole thing
was Fred's idea.

289
00:11:31.892 --> 00:11:33.894
- The guy wanted
a little bit of peace.

290
00:11:33.928 --> 00:11:37.331
- Is it possible that Todd
wanted you all to himself?

291
00:11:37.364 --> 00:11:39.867
- Listen. I am twice divorced.

292
00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:42.369
I am still paying alimony
to the first.

293
00:11:42.403 --> 00:11:45.105
I am not trying to put
a ring on it.

294
00:11:45.139 --> 00:11:48.342
- There's a reason
why Todd is divorced.

295
00:11:48.375 --> 00:11:52.146
Todd is a good time.
like Coney Island.

296
00:11:52.179 --> 00:11:54.782
Fred. on the other hand.

297
00:11:54.815 --> 00:11:58.385
was deep and soulful

298
00:11:58.419 --> 00:12:01.188
and romantic...

299
00:12:01.222 --> 00:12:04.258
like Paris.

300
00:12:04.291 --> 00:12:06.327
Coney Island is fun to visit...

301
00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:09.830
But you don't
move there over Paris.

302
00:12:09.863 --> 00:12:11.198
<i>- What do you think?</i>

303
00:12:11.232 --> 00:12:13.834
- I think people are crazy.
but neither of them

304
00:12:13.867 --> 00:12:15.469
is a physical match
for the shooters. so...

305
00:12:15.503 --> 00:12:17.471
- Still doesn't rule out
murder-for-hire.

306
00:12:17.505 --> 00:12:18.973
- Well. yeah.

307
00:12:19.006 --> 00:12:20.774
- Did you put Wesley
up to this?

308
00:12:20.808 --> 00:12:23.010
- No idea
what you're talking about.

309
00:12:23.043 --> 00:12:25.312
but if it's pissing you off.
I'm happy to take credit.

310
00:12:25.346 --> 00:12:27.781
- If he insists
on moving forward.

311
00:12:27.815 --> 00:12:29.350
I can't guarantee
that I'll be able to keep you

312
00:12:29.383 --> 00:12:30.417
out of the crossfire.

313
00:12:32.853 --> 00:12:35.289
- Did she just threaten me?
- Sure seems like it.

314
00:12:35.322 --> 00:12:38.092
But why?
- No idea.

315
00:12:38.125 --> 00:12:39.460
But I'm gonna find out.

316
00:12:39.493 --> 00:12:42.029
Oh. husband!

317
00:12:42.062 --> 00:12:43.864
- You only call me "husband"
when you're mad.

318
00:12:43.897 --> 00:12:45.466
What did I do?
- You tell me.

319
00:12:45.499 --> 00:12:47.468
Vivian just stopped by.

320
00:12:47.502 --> 00:12:49.236
- She told you
I was running for DA.

321
00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:51.472
- Wait. you're running for DA?
Since when?

322
00:12:51.506 --> 00:12:53.807
- No. no. no. wait. it got
sprung on me this morning.

323
00:12:53.841 --> 00:12:54.942
- What does that mean?

324
00:12:54.975 --> 00:12:55.710
- Some people came
to talk to me

325
00:12:55.744 --> 00:12:57.344
about taking over
Sean's campaign.

326
00:12:57.378 --> 00:13:01.315
- And you told them no.
- I did...initially. but...

327
00:13:01.348 --> 00:13:04.118
- But now you're thinking
about it?

328
00:13:04.151 --> 00:13:06.320
- I mean. I'd at least like
to discuss it.

329
00:13:06.353 --> 00:13:08.822
But I am supposed to be
on my way to court right now.

330
00:13:08.856 --> 00:13:10.090
only Lucy texted to tell me

331
00:13:10.124 --> 00:13:11.425
that our key piece
of evidence is missing.

332
00:13:11.458 --> 00:13:12.926
So is there any chance

333
00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:14.061
that we can just table this
until tonight?

334
00:13:14.094 --> 00:13:16.297
- Fine. but only because
yelling at you in the bullpen

335
00:13:16.330 --> 00:13:17.965
might come across
as unprofessional.

336
00:13:17.998 --> 00:13:19.534
- Thank you. I love you.

337
00:13:23.370 --> 00:13:25.973
Everything okay?

338
00:13:26.006 --> 00:13:27.174
- Are you free
for dinner tonight?

339
00:13:27.207 --> 00:13:28.942
- Depends. Can I bring James?

340
00:13:28.976 --> 00:13:31.478
- As long as you tell him
he has to be Team Lopez.

341
00:13:31.513 --> 00:13:33.380
on the penalty of death.

342
00:13:33.414 --> 00:13:34.549
- I will be sure to prep him.

343
00:13:36.283 --> 00:13:38.886
- I remember Lucy
gave me the machete.

344
00:13:38.919 --> 00:13:40.954
and I logged it
like I always do.

345
00:13:40.988 --> 00:13:43.123
- Okay. so that right there
is the problem. Smitty.

346
00:13:43.157 --> 00:13:44.526
The system changed.

347
00:13:44.559 --> 00:13:46.393
Most of the world
uses day. month. year.

348
00:13:46.427 --> 00:13:48.962
Month. day. year was causing
all of these issues for us

349
00:13:48.996 --> 00:13:50.364
with our international cases.

350
00:13:50.397 --> 00:13:52.333
which is why we switched.
you know?

351
00:13:52.366 --> 00:13:54.636
Didn't you read the memo?

352
00:13:54.669 --> 00:13:56.236
Sorry. wait.

353
00:13:56.270 --> 00:13:57.905
I just heard that out loud.
Of course you didn't.

354
00:13:57.938 --> 00:14:01.576
- Important memos are always
covered in the roll call.

355
00:14:01.609 --> 00:14:04.445
- Why do I have a panicked ADA
knocking on my door

356
00:14:04.478 --> 00:14:06.581
to ask for my help
to find a missing machete?

357
00:14:06.614 --> 00:14:08.882
- Because Smitty
wasn't listening

358
00:14:08.916 --> 00:14:11.151
when you went over the change
in how we file case numbers.

359
00:14:11.185 --> 00:14:13.153
- What.
the "day. month. year" thing?

360
00:14:13.187 --> 00:14:15.155
- Yeah.
- I didn't go over it.

361
00:14:15.189 --> 00:14:17.057
My last day as watch commander
was crazy.

362
00:14:17.091 --> 00:14:19.426
I left it for you to do.
- I thought you handled it.

363
00:14:19.460 --> 00:14:21.061
- Oh. it's not my fault.
It's yours.

364
00:14:21.095 --> 00:14:23.397
- Everyone got the memo.
It's still your fault. Smitty.

365
00:14:23.430 --> 00:14:25.032
- Well. it's still on him
for trusting me.

366
00:14:25.065 --> 00:14:26.433
- I didn't trust you.

367
00:14:26.467 --> 00:14:28.102
I thought he covered it.
and I just didn't follow up.

368
00:14:28.135 --> 00:14:29.504
I can't believe I dropped
the ball like that.

369
00:14:29.537 --> 00:14:30.572
- I don't care
whose fault it is.

370
00:14:30.605 --> 00:14:32.039
I need the machete.

371
00:14:32.072 --> 00:14:34.341
Smitty used
the old system. right?

372
00:14:34.375 --> 00:14:37.277
Try 01-20-2026.

373
00:14:37.311 --> 00:14:39.446
- I-I can't.
It's a dropdown menu.

374
00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:40.648
There's no 20th month.

375
00:14:40.682 --> 00:14:42.282
- What. so you can enter
the 20th month.

376
00:14:42.316 --> 00:14:43.618
but you can't retrieve
the 20th month?

377
00:14:43.651 --> 00:14:45.319
- Correct.
- No. That's wrong.

378
00:14:45.352 --> 00:14:48.188
It shouldn't work that way.
- But that is how it works.

379
00:14:48.222 --> 00:14:51.425
- Wesley says the judge
is losing his patience.

380
00:14:51.458 --> 00:14:52.560
If you can't produce
the evidence.

381
00:14:52.594 --> 00:14:54.328
he's prepared to
dismiss the case.

382
00:14:54.361 --> 00:14:55.597
- Oh.

383
00:14:55.630 --> 00:14:57.297
- Guys. this is
bigger than one case.

384
00:14:57.331 --> 00:14:58.633
Everything Smitty logged
has been misfiled.

385
00:14:58.666 --> 00:15:01.268
going back two months.

386
00:15:01.301 --> 00:15:03.036
<i>- Did the widow shed</i>
<i>some light?</i>

387
00:15:03.070 --> 00:15:04.938
- Uh. not exactly.
but her doorbell cam did.

388
00:15:04.972 --> 00:15:06.173
This is from two days ago.

389
00:15:06.206 --> 00:15:09.176
The car is registered
to a Ryder Frost.

390
00:15:09.209 --> 00:15:11.011
known member
of the Southern Front.

391
00:15:11.044 --> 00:15:12.312
- Well. that tattoo is a match.

392
00:15:12.346 --> 00:15:13.615
Definitely could be
our shooter.

393
00:15:13.648 --> 00:15:15.449
Any idea who
the other fellow is?

394
00:15:15.482 --> 00:15:17.251
- Not yet. but his tats
are 54th Street Gang.

395
00:15:17.284 --> 00:15:20.320
- Besides the racial element.
don't SF and the 5-4

396
00:15:20.354 --> 00:15:22.022
compete for the same
meth business?

397
00:15:22.055 --> 00:15:23.323
- They did
up until a few months ago.

398
00:15:23.357 --> 00:15:25.225
when the Armenians
pushed Southern Front

399
00:15:25.259 --> 00:15:26.493
further into the Valley.

400
00:15:26.528 --> 00:15:28.128
But they are
certainly not allies.

401
00:15:28.162 --> 00:15:30.197
- They cased the garage
but not the house.

402
00:15:30.230 --> 00:15:31.699
Any idea what
they were looking for?

403
00:15:31.733 --> 00:15:33.467
- We've got a last-known
for Ryder.

404
00:15:33.500 --> 00:15:35.035
We were hoping
you'd go ask him.

405
00:15:45.012 --> 00:15:46.013
- Wait.

406
00:15:50.150 --> 00:15:51.385
Control. in pursuit of suspect.

407
00:15:51.418 --> 00:15:53.487
entering Royal Lake
Apartments--send backup.

408
00:16:08.402 --> 00:16:10.170
- Come on. come on.

409
00:16:14.709 --> 00:16:16.644
- Passing third floor.
heading for the roof!

410
00:16:26.086 --> 00:16:29.022
- Stop! LAPD!

411
00:16:29.056 --> 00:16:30.692
Come on. Ryder.

412
00:16:30.725 --> 00:16:32.426
There's nowhere to go.

413
00:16:32.459 --> 00:16:34.529
- Put your hands on your head.
Down on your knees.

414
00:16:38.833 --> 00:16:40.735
- Wait. wait. wait! Stop!
- Stop!

415
00:17:00.187 --> 00:17:02.155
- I'm sorry. are these
cases from the future?

416
00:17:02.189 --> 00:17:04.358
- Apparently. the system didn't
know what to do with month 20.

417
00:17:04.391 --> 00:17:05.225
and so it just made
the math work.

418
00:17:05.259 --> 00:17:08.095
And 12 months plus 8
is August 2027.

419
00:17:08.128 --> 00:17:10.130
- Cases from the 21st became
September of next year.

420
00:17:10.163 --> 00:17:11.699
and so on.
- This is unbelievable.

421
00:17:11.733 --> 00:17:13.433
The judge granted
a continuance.

422
00:17:13.467 --> 00:17:15.603
but we need the machete
by noon tomorrow.

423
00:17:15.637 --> 00:17:17.437
- Yep. Don't worry.
We will have it.

424
00:17:17.471 --> 00:17:18.840
- I'll stick around.
I feel responsible.

425
00:17:18.873 --> 00:17:20.675
- No. it's completely on me.
- I should have clarified.

426
00:17:20.708 --> 00:17:22.309
- You were on your way out.

427
00:17:22.342 --> 00:17:24.311
- Okay. you guys are
both Spartacus. okay?

428
00:17:24.344 --> 00:17:25.445
Let's please start
opening the boxes.

429
00:17:25.479 --> 00:17:27.615
- Are you coming?
- No.

430
00:17:29.216 --> 00:17:31.151
- Russ. I thought you had
a flight to catch.

431
00:17:31.184 --> 00:17:32.587
- I do.
but I couldn't leave LA

432
00:17:32.620 --> 00:17:34.087
without making one last appeal.

433
00:17:34.121 --> 00:17:36.223
- Well. I guess
you better come in. then.

434
00:17:36.256 --> 00:17:38.225
- Thank you.

435
00:17:38.258 --> 00:17:40.628
Oh.

436
00:17:40.662 --> 00:17:43.598
You've really made a nice life
for yourself here. Nune.

437
00:17:43.631 --> 00:17:47.401
I can. uh--I can see why you'd
hesitate before giving it up.

438
00:17:47.434 --> 00:17:49.637
But...

439
00:17:49.671 --> 00:17:52.540
anything I can say
to convince you?

440
00:17:52.574 --> 00:17:53.841
- Can I ask why?

441
00:17:53.875 --> 00:17:56.276
I'm not a doctor
or a scientist.

442
00:17:56.310 --> 00:17:59.747
I don't have a PhD.
Why are you asking me?

443
00:17:59.781 --> 00:18:01.415
- Well. maybe I've been
around long enough

444
00:18:01.448 --> 00:18:03.150
to know that having a few extra
letters after your name

445
00:18:03.183 --> 00:18:04.652
doesn't make you a genius.

446
00:18:04.686 --> 00:18:06.286
I also know that
if I bring you a problem.

447
00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:07.555
you won't rest
until you've looked at it

448
00:18:07.589 --> 00:18:10.157
from every
conceivable angle twice

449
00:18:10.190 --> 00:18:11.593
before bringing me a solution.

450
00:18:11.626 --> 00:18:13.728
- What if I can't find
a solution?

451
00:18:13.761 --> 00:18:15.563
- Hell. girl. that's why
they call it a think tank.

452
00:18:15.597 --> 00:18:17.565
Does me no good to have
a bunch of identical people

453
00:18:17.599 --> 00:18:19.199
with identical viewpoints

454
00:18:19.232 --> 00:18:22.235
looking
in identical directions.

455
00:18:22.269 --> 00:18:24.137
Baseball team can't be
all pitchers.

456
00:18:24.171 --> 00:18:25.707
We need somebody
to play shortstop.

457
00:18:25.740 --> 00:18:29.142
All right. gonna miss my flight
if I don't get going.

458
00:18:29.176 --> 00:18:31.144
So. you know. take a few days
to think about it.

459
00:18:31.178 --> 00:18:33.715
Talk it over with your man
and call me.

460
00:18:33.748 --> 00:18:35.215
- I will.

461
00:18:37.217 --> 00:18:39.587
- You know. Nune.
if you don't want the job

462
00:18:39.621 --> 00:18:41.455
because it's not the right fit
or the right time.

463
00:18:41.488 --> 00:18:42.657
that's fine--I get it.

464
00:18:42.690 --> 00:18:44.525
But deciding that
you're not good enough

465
00:18:44.559 --> 00:18:46.794
before somebody else can...

466
00:18:46.828 --> 00:18:49.764
that's the coward's way.

467
00:18:49.797 --> 00:18:51.866
And I know you're not a coward.

468
00:18:51.899 --> 00:18:54.368
- No. sir. I'm not.

469
00:18:58.205 --> 00:19:00.708
- Giddyup.

470
00:19:06.346 --> 00:19:08.215
- Yeah. all right.

471
00:19:08.248 --> 00:19:10.518
Okay. thanks for the update.

472
00:19:10.551 --> 00:19:12.954
Suspect in the
Central Station Market shooting

473
00:19:12.987 --> 00:19:14.689
fell to his death.
- That's awful.

474
00:19:14.722 --> 00:19:15.957
- Yeah. guy thought
he was an action hero.

475
00:19:15.990 --> 00:19:17.558
tried to leap
between two buildings.

476
00:19:17.592 --> 00:19:19.259
- Any leads
on the second shooter?

477
00:19:19.292 --> 00:19:21.228
- No. but the brass
has been blowing up my phone.

478
00:19:21.261 --> 00:19:22.897
You know. a guy falls to his
death during a police pursuit.

479
00:19:22.930 --> 00:19:25.700
everyone's got questions.

480
00:19:25.733 --> 00:19:28.569
Captain. always a pleasure.

481
00:19:28.603 --> 00:19:30.571
I do not miss that.

482
00:19:30.605 --> 00:19:32.239
- I don't think
I've seen him sleep

483
00:19:32.272 --> 00:19:34.509
more than four consecutive
hours since he took this job.

484
00:19:34.542 --> 00:19:36.476
- I know being sidelined
for the president's visit

485
00:19:36.511 --> 00:19:38.245
shook Tim up.

486
00:19:38.278 --> 00:19:40.748
And even though it was more
of a CYA decision by the brass

487
00:19:40.782 --> 00:19:43.250
than an indictment
on his performance.

488
00:19:43.283 --> 00:19:44.919
the optics weren't great
for him.

489
00:19:44.952 --> 00:19:46.554
- Do you think
he should be worried?

490
00:19:46.587 --> 00:19:49.456
- I think that watch commander
is a thankless job.

491
00:19:49.489 --> 00:19:51.258
You're not in the field.

492
00:19:51.291 --> 00:19:52.359
but you're responsible
for every knucklehead that is.

493
00:19:52.392 --> 00:19:54.529
Patrol officers want resources
you can't give them.

494
00:19:54.562 --> 00:19:56.597
The brass expects results

495
00:19:56.631 --> 00:19:58.966
that you realistically
can't produce.

496
00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:00.802
And when there's bad press

497
00:20:00.835 --> 00:20:02.637
and they're looking
for a head to roll...

498
00:20:02.670 --> 00:20:03.838
- Right.
I didn't think of it that way.

499
00:20:03.871 --> 00:20:04.972
- 'Cause I made it look easy.

500
00:20:06.741 --> 00:20:08.475
He'll get the hang of it.

501
00:20:11.746 --> 00:20:14.015
- The machete! Yes!

502
00:20:14.048 --> 00:20:16.483
I got--I got to call Wesley.
- I'd wait a beat on that.

503
00:20:23.323 --> 00:20:24.692
- Yeah. that sounds horrible.

504
00:20:24.726 --> 00:20:26.861
- It wasn't pretty.
that's for sure.

505
00:20:26.894 --> 00:20:30.297
Nolan and I barely had time to
twitch before it was all over.

506
00:20:30.330 --> 00:20:32.533
- So where does
that leave the case?

507
00:20:32.567 --> 00:20:34.669
- Still trying to ID
the second shooter.

508
00:20:36.838 --> 00:20:39.574
- Hey. did you know
the Armenians

509
00:20:39.607 --> 00:20:41.709
pushed the Southern Front's
meth trade deeper into the--

510
00:20:41.743 --> 00:20:44.311
- Deeper into the Valley?
Yep. happened a few months ago.

511
00:20:44.344 --> 00:20:46.514
- I swear. I read every gang
report the department puts out.

512
00:20:46.547 --> 00:20:48.415
and I haven't seen
anything about that.

513
00:20:48.448 --> 00:20:49.984
- Yeah. see. those reports
only get you so far.

514
00:20:50.017 --> 00:20:52.553
I mean. the best information
is usually

515
00:20:52.587 --> 00:20:54.689
through word of mouth.
which is great for me.

516
00:20:54.722 --> 00:20:57.390
'cause I know people
from all over the city.

517
00:20:57.424 --> 00:21:00.027
- Well. how can I compete
with that when I just got here?

518
00:21:00.061 --> 00:21:01.963
It takes time to cultivate
that kind of trust.

519
00:21:01.996 --> 00:21:04.397
- True. but. I mean.
you'd be shocked

520
00:21:04.431 --> 00:21:06.366
by what some of these
low-level gangbangers

521
00:21:06.399 --> 00:21:07.835
put on social media.

522
00:21:07.869 --> 00:21:10.004
- The LA gang subreddit
is a great resource.

523
00:21:10.037 --> 00:21:12.039
Look. I got to stay up anyway.

524
00:21:12.073 --> 00:21:14.474
I've got a 2:00 a.m. Zoom date
with Rodge.

525
00:21:14.509 --> 00:21:17.545
Why don't I show you some of
my favorite accounts to follow?

526
00:21:17.578 --> 00:21:20.380
Who knows? You might see
something on Ryder.

527
00:21:20.413 --> 00:21:21.916
- Well. all right.
let's go. Coach.

528
00:21:21.949 --> 00:21:23.450
I'm ready.

529
00:21:23.483 --> 00:21:25.653
Hey. Good to see you.

530
00:21:25.686 --> 00:21:27.454
- You too.
- How you doing?

531
00:21:27.487 --> 00:21:30.625
- Thought we might need this.
- Ooh. very thoughtful.

532
00:21:30.658 --> 00:21:31.959
What do you guys think--

533
00:21:31.993 --> 00:21:33.460
should we crack it now
or save it for dinner?

534
00:21:33.493 --> 00:21:34.896
- My vote is now.
- Okay.

535
00:21:34.929 --> 00:21:37.031
- And don't be stingy
with the pours.

536
00:21:38.766 --> 00:21:40.902
Everyone clear on the plan?
- Oh. yes. yes.

537
00:21:40.935 --> 00:21:42.770
James knows--
agree with everything you say

538
00:21:42.804 --> 00:21:45.506
and keep the
starry-eyed-reformer talk

539
00:21:45.540 --> 00:21:47.542
at a minimum.
- Perfect.

540
00:21:47.575 --> 00:21:49.342
Operation: Kill A Dream
is a go.

541
00:21:49.376 --> 00:21:50.511
- Mm-hmm.

542
00:21:50.545 --> 00:21:51.913
He has a point.

543
00:21:51.946 --> 00:21:54.682
We complain all the time
about undocumented witnesses

544
00:21:54.715 --> 00:21:56.617
being too scared to testify.

545
00:21:56.651 --> 00:21:59.954
Instituting a policy that would
protect them from deportation--

546
00:21:59.987 --> 00:22:02.056
that would be a game changer.

547
00:22:02.089 --> 00:22:04.125
I thought we were supposed
to be Team Lopez.

548
00:22:04.158 --> 00:22:06.127
- I know. but it's a good idea.

549
00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:08.495
- I'm not saying
it's not a good idea.

550
00:22:08.529 --> 00:22:11.098
but I think we're getting away
from the larger point.

551
00:22:11.132 --> 00:22:14.669
which is. we'd be opening our
lives up to public scrutiny.

552
00:22:14.702 --> 00:22:17.738
which would be hard enough
for you and me. and...

553
00:22:17.772 --> 00:22:19.774
I worry what it'll do
to the kids.

554
00:22:19.807 --> 00:22:21.809
- So do I.

555
00:22:21.843 --> 00:22:24.411
But I also want them to grow up
knowing that their father

556
00:22:24.444 --> 00:22:26.614
is willing to fight
for the rights of everybody.

557
00:22:26.647 --> 00:22:28.149
even when it's difficult.
- Amen.

558
00:22:29.717 --> 00:22:32.119
- What? You started it.

559
00:22:32.153 --> 00:22:33.988
- Think of what I'd be
in the position to influence

560
00:22:34.021 --> 00:22:35.422
as the DA.

561
00:22:35.455 --> 00:22:37.525
I could end cash bail...

562
00:22:37.558 --> 00:22:40.427
expand victim services.
emphasize counseling.

563
00:22:40.460 --> 00:22:42.530
- Institutional change
is always hard.

564
00:22:42.563 --> 00:22:44.565
- Right. but does that mean
that I shouldn't try?

565
00:22:44.599 --> 00:22:46.499
- What about the house?

566
00:22:46.534 --> 00:22:48.803
- Yeah. well. we would probably
have to wait on that.

567
00:22:48.836 --> 00:22:50.504
I mean. optics would--

568
00:22:50.538 --> 00:22:52.439
- And you'd be fine
letting public perception

569
00:22:52.472 --> 00:22:53.841
dictate how we live our lives?

570
00:22:53.875 --> 00:22:57.178
- In service of real reform...

571
00:22:57.211 --> 00:22:58.679
maybe.

572
00:22:58.713 --> 00:23:01.716
Real change requires sacrifice.

573
00:23:01.749 --> 00:23:03.985
- But I would not do it
at the expense of our family.

574
00:23:04.018 --> 00:23:06.520
I would need to know
that you were on board 100%.

575
00:23:09.624 --> 00:23:11.058
- Hello.

576
00:23:11.092 --> 00:23:14.061
Whoa. Something smells good.

577
00:23:14.095 --> 00:23:16.597
- Because I cooked.

578
00:23:16.631 --> 00:23:17.999
- More than cooked.

579
00:23:18.032 --> 00:23:20.968
Candles? Should I be worried?
- No. not at all.

580
00:23:21.002 --> 00:23:23.004
I just know you had
a really hard day.

581
00:23:23.037 --> 00:23:24.872
and I wanted to do
something nice for you.

582
00:23:24.906 --> 00:23:27.041
- Oh. Uh-huh.

583
00:23:27.074 --> 00:23:28.809
And. uh...

584
00:23:28.843 --> 00:23:30.845
what do you really want
in exchange

585
00:23:30.878 --> 00:23:33.881
for this totally
no-strings-attached feast?

586
00:23:33.915 --> 00:23:36.717
- A conversation...

587
00:23:36.751 --> 00:23:37.985
about D.C.

588
00:23:38.019 --> 00:23:39.954
- I didn't know we
needed to have one.

589
00:23:39.987 --> 00:23:42.056
- I know. and that is my fault.

590
00:23:42.089 --> 00:23:44.191
But all day.

591
00:23:44.225 --> 00:23:47.561
I have not been able to get
this idea out of my head.

592
00:23:47.595 --> 00:23:50.131
And Russ stopped by
on the way to the airport

593
00:23:50.164 --> 00:23:51.933
and gave me his final appeal.

594
00:23:51.966 --> 00:23:54.001
and it made me question

595
00:23:54.035 --> 00:23:56.237
why I was so quick
to shut it down.

596
00:23:56.270 --> 00:23:57.939
- Well--

597
00:23:57.972 --> 00:24:00.241
- And before you tell me no
or give me 100 reasons

598
00:24:00.274 --> 00:24:04.045
why it won't work. all I ask
is that you spend some time

599
00:24:04.078 --> 00:24:06.914
to explore the idea.
- And by that. you mean?

600
00:24:06.948 --> 00:24:09.984
- See what transferring
to D.C. Police would look like.

601
00:24:10.017 --> 00:24:11.719
Make some calls.

602
00:24:11.752 --> 00:24:13.654
ask some questions.
kick the tires.

603
00:24:13.688 --> 00:24:15.022
- And...

604
00:24:15.056 --> 00:24:17.191
what if we come
to different conclusions?

605
00:24:17.224 --> 00:24:19.026
- We abort the mission.

606
00:24:19.060 --> 00:24:21.494
Either we're both in
or both out.

607
00:24:21.529 --> 00:24:23.264
- We need both keys
to launch the torpedoes.

608
00:24:23.297 --> 00:24:24.966
- Yes.

609
00:24:24.999 --> 00:24:26.233
What do you think?

610
00:24:29.036 --> 00:24:31.939
- I think I want you
to be happy.

611
00:24:31.973 --> 00:24:34.542
And if this is
something you want.

612
00:24:34.575 --> 00:24:37.144
then I will do everything
I can from my end

613
00:24:37.178 --> 00:24:38.646
to see if it's feasible.

614
00:24:40.281 --> 00:24:42.249
We're in this together.

615
00:24:49.090 --> 00:24:50.124
- Is it just me.

616
00:24:50.157 --> 00:24:51.225
or are these numbers
starting to blend together?

617
00:24:51.258 --> 00:24:52.927
- It is not just you.

618
00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:54.662
- Hey. everything okay
with the brass?

619
00:24:54.695 --> 00:24:57.765
- Ryder's death was ruled
an accident.

620
00:24:57.798 --> 00:24:59.834
but there's always a chance
they could reopen the case

621
00:24:59.867 --> 00:25:02.837
or blame me for this whole
evidence-logging mess.

622
00:25:02.870 --> 00:25:04.271
- Hey. just take the win.

623
00:25:04.305 --> 00:25:06.807
- You're right.

624
00:25:06.841 --> 00:25:09.110
Look. I swear.
if I lose watch commander

625
00:25:09.143 --> 00:25:11.145
because of Smitty--
- That's not gonna happen.

626
00:25:11.178 --> 00:25:12.947
I have been manifesting

627
00:25:12.980 --> 00:25:14.815
that we will find
this machete all day.

628
00:25:14.849 --> 00:25:16.784
- "Manifesting"?
- Mm-hmm.

629
00:25:16.817 --> 00:25:18.819
- God. I got you away
from Juarez just in time.

630
00:25:18.853 --> 00:25:20.287
Shut up.

631
00:25:22.289 --> 00:25:24.658
- You got to be kidding me.
- Hmm?

632
00:25:27.028 --> 00:25:28.295
Oh. my God.

633
00:25:30.664 --> 00:25:32.933
This is it! This is it!
- Thank God.

634
00:25:32.967 --> 00:25:34.735
All right. let's go home.
- Okay.

635
00:25:34.769 --> 00:25:35.736
Whoo!

636
00:25:37.338 --> 00:25:40.741
- Hey. where are you?
<i>- A yurt in Finland.</i>

637
00:25:40.775 --> 00:25:43.577
<i>The Northern Lights have been</i>
<i>amazing the last few nights.</i>

638
00:25:43.611 --> 00:25:45.212
- Jealous.

639
00:25:45.246 --> 00:25:46.180
<i>- I know. I wish you were</i>
<i>here to see them with me.</i>

640
00:25:46.213 --> 00:25:48.182
- Me too. I miss you.

641
00:25:48.215 --> 00:25:50.017
- Hey. Celina.
I might have found something.

642
00:25:50.051 --> 00:25:51.585
So Ryder--

643
00:25:51.619 --> 00:25:53.187
<i>- Is that Miles? Hey. Miles.</i>
- Hey. man.

644
00:25:53.220 --> 00:25:55.122
How's the Great White North?
- He saw the aurora.

645
00:25:55.156 --> 00:25:56.357
- Oh. cool.
<i>- Who's Ryder?</i>

646
00:25:56.390 --> 00:25:58.893
- A suspect in a murder.
<i>- Well. that sounds important.</i>

647
00:25:58.926 --> 00:26:01.862
<i>Do you need to go?</i>
- No. Just give me one second.

648
00:26:01.896 --> 00:26:03.297
What's up?

649
00:26:03.330 --> 00:26:05.266
- Okay. so I was looking
through Ryder's juvie file.

650
00:26:05.299 --> 00:26:06.934
Between the ages of 9 to 14.

651
00:26:06.967 --> 00:26:08.836
he lived
in four different foster homes.

652
00:26:08.869 --> 00:26:11.172
One was located
in the 54th Street territory.

653
00:26:11.205 --> 00:26:13.974
Foster parents were
Mabel and Rafael Sinclair.

654
00:26:14.008 --> 00:26:16.277
And Rafael died
a few years ago--heart attack.

655
00:26:16.310 --> 00:26:19.346
But look at what
I found on Mabel.

656
00:26:23.084 --> 00:26:25.052
- Uh. babe. I'm sorry.
I got to go.

657
00:26:25.086 --> 00:26:27.655
<i>- No worries. Uh. have fun</i>
<i>solving your murder.</i>

658
00:26:27.688 --> 00:26:29.056
- We will.

659
00:26:29.090 --> 00:26:31.625
Let me see.

660
00:26:31.659 --> 00:26:33.627
This is Mabel Sinclair.

661
00:26:33.661 --> 00:26:36.030
- Most of the kids in the
neighborhood just call her Ma.

662
00:26:36.063 --> 00:26:37.932
since they know
whatever they need--

663
00:26:37.965 --> 00:26:39.867
food. a place to stay.
clean clothes--

664
00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:41.368
Mabel will hook them up.

665
00:26:41.402 --> 00:26:43.003
- Well. last week Mabel was
the victim of a hit-and-run

666
00:26:43.037 --> 00:26:44.672
while crossing her street.

667
00:26:44.705 --> 00:26:46.707
Witnesses saw a red sedan
speeding away from the scene.

668
00:26:46.740 --> 00:26:48.342
but no arrests have been made.

669
00:26:48.375 --> 00:26:50.878
Anyone care to guess what
kind of car Fred Wilson drove?

670
00:26:50.911 --> 00:26:52.346
A red Camry.

671
00:26:52.379 --> 00:26:54.949
- So you think Fred hit Mabel?
- Oh. more than that.

672
00:26:54.982 --> 00:26:56.784
Celina ran his VIN

673
00:26:56.817 --> 00:26:59.220
and found the body shop
doing the repairs on his car.

674
00:26:59.253 --> 00:27:01.922
The bumper tested positive
for blood.

675
00:27:01.956 --> 00:27:03.257
- Forensics are
running the sample.

676
00:27:03.290 --> 00:27:04.959
- What's Ryder's connection
to this woman?

677
00:27:04.992 --> 00:27:06.727
- Oh. Mabel was
his foster mother.

678
00:27:09.697 --> 00:27:11.165
- That's the second shooter.

679
00:27:11.198 --> 00:27:12.666
- That is Kingston Holmes--

680
00:27:12.700 --> 00:27:14.735
22. proud member of the 5-4

681
00:27:14.768 --> 00:27:17.138
and former foster brother
to Ryder Frost.

682
00:27:17.171 --> 00:27:20.407
- So they murdered Fred Wilson
as revenge for killing Mabel.

683
00:27:20.441 --> 00:27:22.109
- Well...

684
00:27:22.143 --> 00:27:23.978
Mabel isn't dead.

685
00:27:26.213 --> 00:27:29.083
- All I remember is going out

686
00:27:29.116 --> 00:27:32.953
to bring my trash cans in
and then waking up here.

687
00:27:32.987 --> 00:27:35.389
and they told me
it was a-a hit-and-run.

688
00:27:35.422 --> 00:27:37.258
- Unfortunately.
the man suspected

689
00:27:37.291 --> 00:27:39.059
of hitting you with his car
was murdered.

690
00:27:39.093 --> 00:27:41.929
We have reason to believe
your former foster sons.

691
00:27:41.962 --> 00:27:44.131
Ryder Frost
and Kingston Holmes.

692
00:27:44.165 --> 00:27:46.767
wanted revenge
for what happened to you.

693
00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:48.769
- It was painful enough

694
00:27:48.802 --> 00:27:51.205
losing Ryder and Kingston
to the streets.

695
00:27:51.238 --> 00:27:52.973
I don't think I can take

696
00:27:53.007 --> 00:27:56.710
knowing that they killed
a man because of me.

697
00:27:58.212 --> 00:28:01.081
- We're very sorry.
but I'm afraid that's not all.

698
00:28:01.115 --> 00:28:04.051
Ryder died yesterday trying
to jump between rooftops.

699
00:28:04.084 --> 00:28:06.921
They were just hurt little boys

700
00:28:06.954 --> 00:28:08.489
underneath it all. you know?

701
00:28:08.523 --> 00:28:11.859
When Ryder first came to us.

702
00:28:11.892 --> 00:28:14.161
he was...

703
00:28:14.195 --> 00:28:16.163
so shut down.

704
00:28:16.197 --> 00:28:20.234
he barely said two words to me
that first month.

705
00:28:20.267 --> 00:28:24.438
But Kingston--he always had
this way about him.

706
00:28:24.471 --> 00:28:26.974
this lightness...

707
00:28:27.007 --> 00:28:30.878
even after all
he'd been through.

708
00:28:30.911 --> 00:28:34.014
But then...

709
00:28:34.048 --> 00:28:37.184
they started to
do everything together.

710
00:28:37.218 --> 00:28:39.153
and bit by bit...

711
00:28:41.255 --> 00:28:43.457
I got to see Ryder

712
00:28:43.490 --> 00:28:47.328
for the sweet.
sensitive boy he was.

713
00:28:47.361 --> 00:28:49.096
- What happened?

714
00:28:49.129 --> 00:28:52.099
- Ryder's mom
came back into the picture

715
00:28:52.132 --> 00:28:54.201
with her skinhead boyfriend.

716
00:28:54.235 --> 00:28:56.170
And once he was gone.

717
00:28:56.203 --> 00:29:00.307
all of Kingston's light
went with him.

718
00:29:00.341 --> 00:29:03.110
He started to...

719
00:29:03.143 --> 00:29:06.914
act out. getting in trouble.

720
00:29:06.947 --> 00:29:09.149
And he was finally put away

721
00:29:09.183 --> 00:29:13.053
on some trumped-up
vandalism charge.

722
00:29:13.087 --> 00:29:17.224
And then he joined the gang

723
00:29:17.258 --> 00:29:20.094
in prison.

724
00:29:20.127 --> 00:29:22.863
And suddenly...

725
00:29:22.896 --> 00:29:27.101
the two boys
I saw become brothers

726
00:29:27.134 --> 00:29:31.905
were turned into mortal enemies
by the streets.

727
00:29:31.939 --> 00:29:34.275
- I'm sorry for how much pain
this has caused you.

728
00:29:34.308 --> 00:29:36.176
but we'd like to bring
Kingston in

729
00:29:36.210 --> 00:29:38.379
without any more bloodshed.

730
00:29:38.412 --> 00:29:40.481
Do you have any way
of contacting him?

731
00:29:44.451 --> 00:29:46.020
What do you want me to say?

732
00:29:48.022 --> 00:29:49.857
- Hey. the judge signed off
on the wiretap.

733
00:29:49.890 --> 00:29:51.492
We should be good
to go in a few.

734
00:29:51.526 --> 00:29:54.962
- Great. Uh. what you were
saying yesterday about D.C.

735
00:29:54.995 --> 00:29:57.331
and needing to unclench...

736
00:29:57.364 --> 00:29:59.933
It can't be that bad. right?

737
00:29:59.967 --> 00:30:03.304
- All right. maybe I'm just--
I've been spoiled by LA.

738
00:30:03.337 --> 00:30:05.306
I'm sure the city has a lot
of great things about it.

739
00:30:05.339 --> 00:30:07.341
but from what I saw.

740
00:30:07.374 --> 00:30:10.444
being a cop there just means
a lot of crowd control

741
00:30:10.477 --> 00:30:13.480
around government offices.
usually in crappy weather--

742
00:30:13.515 --> 00:30:15.382
snowstorms in the winter.

743
00:30:15.416 --> 00:30:18.118
swamp-like humidity
in the summer.

744
00:30:18.152 --> 00:30:21.221
You get two weeks
of cherry blossoms a year.

745
00:30:21.255 --> 00:30:22.557
and that's about it.

746
00:30:22.590 --> 00:30:24.191
- Oh.

747
00:30:24.224 --> 00:30:26.160
- Also. speaking as someone
who thought transferring

748
00:30:26.193 --> 00:30:28.028
to another department
would be easy.

749
00:30:28.062 --> 00:30:29.564
be prepared to relearn

750
00:30:29.597 --> 00:30:31.633
everything
you thought you knew.

751
00:30:31.666 --> 00:30:33.300
- Yeah.
All right. we got to go.

752
00:30:46.246 --> 00:30:48.248
- Mama?
- It's me. baby.

753
00:30:48.282 --> 00:30:49.950
- Oh. thank God.

754
00:30:49.983 --> 00:30:51.418
I tried to visit you
in the ICU.

755
00:30:51.452 --> 00:30:53.187
but they said
blood family only.

756
00:30:53.220 --> 00:30:54.622
<i>They made it sound</i>
<i>like you were dying.</i>

757
00:30:54.656 --> 00:30:57.659
- Well. I am a little banged
up. but I'll be all right.

758
00:30:57.692 --> 00:31:00.327
- I wish I could come see you.
<i>- Well. me too.</i>

759
00:31:00.361 --> 00:31:02.963
You heard about Ryder?

760
00:31:05.199 --> 00:31:08.102
- Uh. you know. me and Ryder
don't really

761
00:31:08.135 --> 00:31:10.104
mess with each other anymore.

762
00:31:10.137 --> 00:31:12.607
- He's dead. baby. killed.

763
00:31:12.640 --> 00:31:16.611
running away
from what you boys did.

764
00:31:16.644 --> 00:31:19.046
- I don't know
what you're talking about.

765
00:31:19.079 --> 00:31:23.117
<i>- Kingston. please.</i>
<i>You never were a good liar.</i>

766
00:31:25.452 --> 00:31:28.155
You need to turn yourself in.

767
00:31:28.188 --> 00:31:29.624
- I can't.

768
00:31:29.657 --> 00:31:31.392
You know what happened
the last time I went inside.

769
00:31:31.425 --> 00:31:33.360
I had to join the 5-4
just to make it out alive.

770
00:31:33.394 --> 00:31:35.362
- Well. what other
choice do you have?

771
00:31:35.396 --> 00:31:37.097
- Just don't worry
about me. Mama. okay?

772
00:31:37.131 --> 00:31:38.533
Just don't worry.

773
00:31:38.566 --> 00:31:41.468
I got a way out into Mexico.
where I can disappear.

774
00:31:41.503 --> 00:31:44.506
- "Mexico"? What the heck
do you know about Mexico?

775
00:31:44.539 --> 00:31:45.939
- You know what?

776
00:31:45.973 --> 00:31:47.408
Kingston. this is
Detective Nyla Harper

777
00:31:47.441 --> 00:31:48.610
<i>of the LAPD.</i>

778
00:31:48.643 --> 00:31:50.477
- You're working with the cops?

779
00:31:50.512 --> 00:31:52.514
- She is trying
to save your life.

780
00:31:52.547 --> 00:31:55.583
Listen to me--if you run.
things will end badly for you.

781
00:31:55.617 --> 00:31:58.118
But if you turn yourself in.
we can try and help you--

782
00:32:02.022 --> 00:32:03.023
- Please!

783
00:32:03.056 --> 00:32:04.458
He's scared.

784
00:32:04.491 --> 00:32:06.561
Don't hurt him.

785
00:32:06.594 --> 00:32:08.596
- He's not a kid anymore.
Ms. Sinclair.

786
00:32:08.630 --> 00:32:11.432
He killed a man in cold blood.
- So now we have to go get him.

787
00:32:32.687 --> 00:32:34.455
- Yo.

788
00:32:34.488 --> 00:32:35.989
What's up. K?

789
00:32:36.023 --> 00:32:38.225
- They got you working
the door already. huh?

790
00:32:38.258 --> 00:32:41.094
Damn. Lil Trey on the come-up.

791
00:32:41.128 --> 00:32:43.731
- 5-4 for life.

792
00:32:54.776 --> 00:32:58.780
- Oh!
- Yo. P-Mac.

793
00:32:58.813 --> 00:33:00.782
Uh. can we talk?
- Sure.

794
00:33:00.815 --> 00:33:03.217
Come here.

795
00:33:03.250 --> 00:33:06.019
You good?
- Uh...

796
00:33:07.622 --> 00:33:10.357
- Talk to me.

797
00:33:10.390 --> 00:33:13.193
- Uh. I-I got to--

798
00:33:13.227 --> 00:33:15.128
I got to get out of town.

799
00:33:15.162 --> 00:33:17.765
You--you got that hookup with
the cartel tunnels into Mexico?

800
00:33:17.799 --> 00:33:19.333
- For sure.

801
00:33:19.366 --> 00:33:21.468
But why? What happened?

802
00:33:21.503 --> 00:33:23.070
- The less you know.
the better.

803
00:33:23.103 --> 00:33:24.672
Just trust me on that.

804
00:33:24.706 --> 00:33:27.274
- You say "trust me."
I trust you. okay?

805
00:33:27.307 --> 00:33:29.176
I'll make a few phone calls.

806
00:33:29.209 --> 00:33:31.613
Look. relax. all right?
Have a drink.

807
00:33:31.646 --> 00:33:34.147
You know we got you.

808
00:33:34.181 --> 00:33:35.249
- Yeah.

809
00:33:51.231 --> 00:33:52.299
- Yo.

810
00:33:52.332 --> 00:33:53.701
What--

811
00:33:53.735 --> 00:33:56.203
- I truly didn't believe
you'd be stupid enough

812
00:33:56.236 --> 00:33:58.171
to bring your dumb ass
back around here

813
00:33:58.205 --> 00:34:01.441
after all the disrespect
shown us.

814
00:34:01.475 --> 00:34:03.645
Yeah. you hitting civilians.

815
00:34:03.678 --> 00:34:05.813
You working with Nazis.

816
00:34:05.847 --> 00:34:09.116
- Trace on Kingston's phone
landed at 4700 Hilldale.

817
00:34:09.149 --> 00:34:10.350
<i>- Copy that.</i>

818
00:34:12.787 --> 00:34:13.755
- Pull over up here.

819
00:34:16.891 --> 00:34:18.793
- But the address is
on the next block.

820
00:34:18.826 --> 00:34:21.361
- Yeah. you recognize that tag?

821
00:34:21.395 --> 00:34:24.164
- 54th Street.

822
00:34:24.197 --> 00:34:26.768
We roll up hot. they could
have spotters anywhere.

823
00:34:26.801 --> 00:34:28.302
- Exactly. Let's go.

824
00:34:35.409 --> 00:34:38.713
- Yo. young'un.
it's your big moment. man.

825
00:34:38.746 --> 00:34:40.748
This is the moment you prove
how much you love the streets

826
00:34:40.782 --> 00:34:42.482
by taking care
of a traitor-ass bitch

827
00:34:42.517 --> 00:34:44.184
that's disrespecting them.

828
00:34:44.217 --> 00:34:47.387
This is the moment you prove
to me you a good soldier

829
00:34:47.421 --> 00:34:49.156
and you follow orders.
all right?

830
00:34:49.189 --> 00:34:51.726
And in return. the streets
gonna love you back.

831
00:34:51.759 --> 00:34:56.229
And wherever you go.
the 5-4 will follow...

832
00:34:56.263 --> 00:34:57.464
for life.

833
00:34:57.497 --> 00:34:59.299
Now. you take care
of this bitch.

834
00:35:18.620 --> 00:35:20.320
We ain't got all day.

835
00:35:25.593 --> 00:35:26.894
- SWAT's ten minutes out.

836
00:35:26.928 --> 00:35:28.596
You got eyes on Kingston?
- Yeah.

837
00:35:28.630 --> 00:35:30.297
We're looking at a potential
murder in progress.

838
00:35:30.330 --> 00:35:31.398
We can't wait.

839
00:35:34.736 --> 00:35:37.839
Now. smoke this fool.

840
00:35:40.975 --> 00:35:42.610
- Police!
- It's the cops!

841
00:35:42.644 --> 00:35:44.211
Go. go. go!
- Hey!

842
00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:48.916
- Police! Drop your weapons!

843
00:35:55.322 --> 00:35:57.290
- Show me your hands
if you're up there!

844
00:36:04.331 --> 00:36:05.265
- Juarez!

845
00:36:06.868 --> 00:36:08.368
- Go! Go!

846
00:36:10.672 --> 00:36:12.205
Cover us. Go!

847
00:36:20.715 --> 00:36:22.850
- Stay down! Stay down!

848
00:36:34.562 --> 00:36:35.763
- Wait!

849
00:36:55.449 --> 00:36:57.985
- Wait. wait. wait. wait.
Please. please. please.

850
00:36:58.019 --> 00:37:00.353
Please. please.

851
00:37:00.387 --> 00:37:04.025
Please. you can--you can just
say that you didn't see me.

852
00:37:04.058 --> 00:37:05.693
You can say
that you didn't see me.

853
00:37:05.727 --> 00:37:06.928
You can say
that you didn't see me.

854
00:37:06.961 --> 00:37:08.328
Trey. please. Please.

855
00:37:08.361 --> 00:37:09.664
- Get on your stomach.

856
00:37:09.697 --> 00:37:11.298
- Go.

857
00:37:13.935 --> 00:37:16.604
- Drop the gun.
Hands on your head.

858
00:37:35.957 --> 00:37:38.993
- The kid is processed.
- Ah. thank you for that.

859
00:37:39.026 --> 00:37:42.029
Um. look. I realize
this was a bit of a tough one.

860
00:37:42.063 --> 00:37:45.398
You all right?
- I'll be all right.

861
00:37:45.432 --> 00:37:48.301
I know I shouldn't feel
sympathy. but...

862
00:37:48.335 --> 00:37:49.837
he's just a boy.

863
00:37:49.871 --> 00:37:52.573
- Look. no one is saying
you can't feel sympathy.

864
00:37:52.607 --> 00:37:53.875
But at the end of the day.

865
00:37:53.908 --> 00:37:55.777
he did make the choice
to pull that trigger.

866
00:37:57.645 --> 00:37:58.946
Look. why don't you go home?

867
00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:00.815
I'll take care
of the paperwork.

868
00:38:00.848 --> 00:38:02.449
- Yes. sir. Thank you.

869
00:38:02.482 --> 00:38:04.585
- You bet.

870
00:38:04.619 --> 00:38:06.020
- Um...

871
00:38:08.122 --> 00:38:11.959
- It amazes me how one man
can wreak such havoc

872
00:38:11.993 --> 00:38:13.561
on the entire LAPD.

873
00:38:13.594 --> 00:38:15.863
- Smitty is a force of nature.

874
00:38:15.897 --> 00:38:18.032
- Uh. got a minute?
- Yeah. sure. What's up?

875
00:38:18.065 --> 00:38:21.903
- Well. Bailey has been offered
a pretty impressive job

876
00:38:21.936 --> 00:38:24.639
in D.C.--
a Pentagon think tank.

877
00:38:24.672 --> 00:38:28.341
And I was just wondering
what a transfer to the D.C. PD

878
00:38:28.375 --> 00:38:30.011
would be like.

879
00:38:30.044 --> 00:38:33.614
- Yeah. I can get you in touch
with a few people.

880
00:38:33.648 --> 00:38:35.516
But you do know
you would have to start

881
00:38:35.550 --> 00:38:38.519
at the very bottom again.
including redoing the academy?

882
00:38:38.553 --> 00:38:39.987
- I've done it before.

883
00:38:40.021 --> 00:38:41.622
- You were also
five years younger.

884
00:38:41.656 --> 00:38:43.024
- Yes.

885
00:38:43.057 --> 00:38:45.626
- You would get
a pretty hefty signing bonus.

886
00:38:45.660 --> 00:38:46.861
- Well. that's a perk.

887
00:38:46.894 --> 00:38:48.461
- But your annual salary

888
00:38:48.495 --> 00:38:50.665
would be much less
than you make in LA.

889
00:38:50.698 --> 00:38:53.568
Plus. the cost of living
in D.C. is just as expensive.

890
00:38:53.601 --> 00:38:54.969
So. in the long run.

891
00:38:55.002 --> 00:38:57.538
your bonus really won't make
a difference.

892
00:38:57.572 --> 00:39:00.041
especially if Bailey's only
making a government salary.

893
00:39:00.074 --> 00:39:01.843
- Right.

894
00:39:01.876 --> 00:39:03.511
- I'm sorry if this is not the
answer you were looking for.

895
00:39:03.544 --> 00:39:06.647
- No. no. that's. um...

896
00:39:06.681 --> 00:39:08.649
I was just looking
for the truth.

897
00:39:08.683 --> 00:39:11.384
- Yeah. well. good luck.

898
00:39:11.418 --> 00:39:12.687
- Thank you.

899
00:39:14.755 --> 00:39:15.823
- Hey.

900
00:39:17.892 --> 00:39:20.761
The LAPD would be sad
to see you go.

901
00:39:20.795 --> 00:39:23.097
- Thank you. sir.

902
00:39:28.970 --> 00:39:30.938
- Guess what.
- What?

903
00:39:30.972 --> 00:39:33.174
- We won.
- That's great.

904
00:39:33.207 --> 00:39:35.710
Judge give you any grief
about the evidence?

905
00:39:35.743 --> 00:39:38.579
- I think he was too confused
by the explanation

906
00:39:38.613 --> 00:39:39.881
to challenge it.

907
00:39:39.914 --> 00:39:41.883
- Take the win.
- Mm-hmm.

908
00:39:41.916 --> 00:39:43.150
- I prepared
a ten-minute lecture

909
00:39:43.184 --> 00:39:44.719
for tomorrow's roll call

910
00:39:44.752 --> 00:39:46.787
to make sure no one can ever
again use ignorance

911
00:39:46.821 --> 00:39:48.823
as an excuse
when mislabeling case numbers.

912
00:39:48.856 --> 00:39:51.959
- You know. you're a really
good watch commander.

913
00:39:51.993 --> 00:39:53.527
- I'm figuring it out.

914
00:39:53.561 --> 00:39:55.129
- No. listen. no matter
what kind of craziness

915
00:39:55.162 --> 00:39:56.697
is going on at the station.

916
00:39:56.731 --> 00:39:58.900
you're always
the center of calm.

917
00:39:58.933 --> 00:40:01.468
And the rest of us need that.
I need that.

918
00:40:01.501 --> 00:40:03.204
- Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

919
00:40:03.237 --> 00:40:05.006
- I'll tell you what--

920
00:40:05.039 --> 00:40:07.041
list of things we can't trust
Smitty with is getting longer.

921
00:40:07.074 --> 00:40:09.176
- Do you think he's doing it
on purpose?

922
00:40:09.210 --> 00:40:10.912
- Weaponized incompetence?
- Yeah.

923
00:40:10.945 --> 00:40:12.079
- I don't think
he's that strategic.

924
00:40:19.921 --> 00:40:22.023
- Hey.
Sorry I missed dinner...

925
00:40:23.958 --> 00:40:25.593
And bedtime.

926
00:40:27.528 --> 00:40:30.631
- You should run for DA.

927
00:40:30.665 --> 00:40:33.701
- Are you sure?
Because if you're not in 100%--

928
00:40:33.734 --> 00:40:35.136
- I'm in.

929
00:40:35.169 --> 00:40:37.071
The more I thought about it.
the more I realized

930
00:40:37.104 --> 00:40:40.041
this was exactly
why you joined the DA's office

931
00:40:40.074 --> 00:40:42.677
in the first place.
- Hmm.

932
00:40:42.710 --> 00:40:45.513
- And I'm proud you want to set
that example for our children.

933
00:40:45.546 --> 00:40:47.581
especially because every day
I see firsthand

934
00:40:47.615 --> 00:40:50.217
the people
our system has failed.

935
00:40:50.251 --> 00:40:53.154
And. inevitably.
the ones who suffer the most

936
00:40:53.187 --> 00:40:55.790
are other kids.

937
00:40:55.823 --> 00:40:57.925
- Are you sure you're okay
waiting on a new house?

938
00:40:57.959 --> 00:40:59.694
No.

939
00:40:59.727 --> 00:41:02.063
- But like you said.

940
00:41:02.096 --> 00:41:05.866
real change requires sacrifice.

941
00:41:05.900 --> 00:41:08.736
And I love this house.

942
00:41:08.769 --> 00:41:11.272
We brought home
two babies here.

943
00:41:11.305 --> 00:41:13.774
- Mm.

944
00:41:13.808 --> 00:41:16.177
We also made two babies here.

945
00:41:16.210 --> 00:41:18.112
So we did.

946
00:41:21.916 --> 00:41:24.719
- No food
to entice me with. I see.

947
00:41:24.752 --> 00:41:27.487
- No. but I have wine.

948
00:41:30.157 --> 00:41:32.660
- Listen. I don't want to beat
around the bush.

949
00:41:32.693 --> 00:41:35.730
I did my due diligence.
and I am sorry. honey.

950
00:41:35.763 --> 00:41:38.032
I don't think I can do D.C.

951
00:41:38.065 --> 00:41:40.868
It would mean starting

952
00:41:40.901 --> 00:41:43.671
all over again as a rookie.

953
00:41:43.704 --> 00:41:46.607
Only this time.
instead of being 45. I'd be 50.

954
00:41:46.640 --> 00:41:47.842
- Oh.

955
00:41:50.211 --> 00:41:51.846
What if...

956
00:41:53.781 --> 00:41:56.717
I'm not ready to say no?

957
00:41:56.751 --> 00:42:00.221
- Well. you did say
we both had to be in.

958
00:42:00.254 --> 00:42:01.956
or you would walk away.

959
00:42:01.989 --> 00:42:06.627
- I know. and I meant it
when I said it.

960
00:42:06.660 --> 00:42:08.596
But now...

961
00:42:08.629 --> 00:42:10.097
- You still want it?

962
00:42:12.767 --> 00:42:15.002
- So where does that leave us?

963
00:42:54.041 --> 00:42:54.775
<i>- Damn it.</i>
